		<div class="postbody">
			<div class="postrow">
				
				
				<h2 class="title icon icon0">
					Re: [Expansion] Reaper of Souls
				</h2>
				

						
						
				<div class="content">
					<div id="post_message_1793505">
						<blockquote class="postcontent restore ">
							<div class="bbcode_container">
	<div class="bbcode_quote">
		<div class="quote_container">
			<div class="bbcode_quote_container"></div>
			
				<div class="bbcode_postedby">
					<img src="images/misc/quote_icon.png" alt="Quote" /> Originally Posted by <strong>Wool</strong>
					<a href="showthread.php?s=f65c4bd7286cdcffe68d99cdcc259a03&amp;p=1793501#post1793501" rel="nofollow"><img class="inlineimg" src="images/buttons/viewpost-right.png" alt="View Post" /></a>
				</div>
				<div class="message">Nooo, how will I get a free copy of Legacy of the Void now?<br />
<br />
I really don't think the AH is the problem as much as the itemization. There's nothing wrong with buying some rare thing you don't need. The problem is when you need (or feel like you need) to buy a thing just to advance because the drops you are capable of getting aren't good enough.</div>
			
		</div>
	</div>
</div>The AH was a <i>great</i>, innovative and <b>needed</b> component to address the realities associated with an online game like Diablo, however the way they implemented it completely sabotaged the benefits of doing so, and then they did the incredibly unsmart thing of not acting upon their own data to correct flaws that arose in the implementation. As but one example, Blizzard set a minimum price per stack of gold, which made that gold unsellable for long periods of time until they manually adjusted it to allowed to be lower, so the only way to sell gold was to sell it on a grey market, which entirely defeats the purpose of having a RMAH in the first place and ensures that the game attracts a criminal element. They also set a price maximum that was orders of magnitude too low to address the real world value of an item. As an example, the gold maximum was set at 2 billion gold, yet items existed whose real world market value was thousands of USD. There was and possibly still is no way to sell that on the RMAH; a rational actor is <i>forced</i> to sell it in a grey market to avoid cutting off their own legs. And in the event that someone did do so, a rational observer has to buy that item and resell it at its real price on a grey market. Market manipulation was also extremely prevalent due to how easy it was to corner a market within a low probable niche. And people had tens of accounts at once to market all of their goods, something which was profitable thanks to the game only being a sunk cost. Blizzard did nothing to address those market behaviours, and insisted that there were only four elements in the universe despite all evidence and everyone paying attention telling them they were off their rockers for months. That requires a special level of ineptitude at many levels of the corporation as the long term profit from the RMAH would easily eclipse the initial game licenses (assuming that Blizzard does not release a Diablo 4 in the near future or shut down the servers). Blizzard did not even have the excuse of having no model to utilize or there existing no theory to use as a basis for their implementation. There are no words that can rationalize that magnitude of sheer incompetence.
						</blockquote>
					</div>

					
				</div>
			</div>
			
