		<div class="postbody">
			<div class="postrow">
				
				
				<h2 class="title icon icon0">
					Re: [Expansion] Reaper of Souls
				</h2>
				

						
						
				<div class="content">
					<div id="post_message_1794126">
						<blockquote class="postcontent restore ">
							<div class="bbcode_container">
	<div class="bbcode_quote">
		<div class="quote_container">
			<div class="bbcode_quote_container"></div>
			
				<div class="bbcode_postedby">
					<img src="images/misc/quote_icon.png" alt="Quote" /> Originally Posted by <strong>Maledict</strong>
					<a href="showthread.php?s=f65c4bd7286cdcffe68d99cdcc259a03&amp;p=1793891#post1793891" rel="nofollow"><img class="inlineimg" src="images/buttons/viewpost-right.png" alt="View Post" /></a>
				</div>
				<div class="message">Think we may be talking at cross purposes here.<br />
<br />
There will always be a black market. There is now even with the AH. My  point was that the number of people using that market was relatively  small compared to the overall player base and as such it had a very  limited effect on the game.<br />
<br />
Compare that to a game where there are zero barriers to entry and you  basically force people to use that marketplace whether they want to or  not. <br />
<br />
Let the people who want to trade on d2jsp trade. Just don't enable them  ingame and then let the entire game warp around them. Introducing the AH  because people made money on d2jsp was an unnecessary solution to a  problem that didn't exist.</div>
			
		</div>
	</div>
</div>I disagree. There is no motivation for a black market when the  alternative is easier and has less risk associate with it provided that  fencing the goods will achieve the highest return on the legitimate  market after risk of fraud is factored in. The last requirement is where  Blizzard messed up horribly in their implementation, neglecting any  other factors that could have been improved upon it. They also designed  the AH such that participation in it was mandatory unless the player has  sensational and ongoing luck obtaining items and the vast majority of  people do not enjoy playing banker outside of work/life requirements,  however a fraction do and end up accounting for the vast majority of the  markets. With the hard cap on goods sold per account etc. that  attempted to prevent the small fraction from having their preferred fun  Blizzard ignored that and just made the game worse for everyone. The end  result was that the majority of players were miserable and trade  enthusiasts just purchased shit loads of accounts to overcome the limit,  making at least one motivation for having such a limit pointless. FWIW,  the game whose economy implementation I have found the most fun is  Recettear. That game is worse than EQ for me and completely absorbs me  when playing it. The reason being that it has a fun and strategical  economy/trade game, however the combat is very fun too (if you like  early FF games combat anyways). The main ongoing issue I had with D3 is  that I cannot play hardcore reasonably while having to deal with latency  and server-side hiccups that result in me dying and losing all of my  shit for no fault of my own, it is not possible to play on a local lan  either, and it has mandatory DRM. D3 entirely killed the notion of  always-on DRM for me in any context ever again and will not ever spend  time or money on a system which has such at the cost of gameplay  quality. There's no reason that I should not be able to mod/hack a  single player game or host user created settings locally and even on the  Internet, especially in the context of how little content Diablo 3 had.  I hate how anti-fun/anti-creativity gaming is moving towards, even on  the PC platform. I really, really wanted D3 to succeed and be awesome as  I love games like it, but the implementation was not fun to play for  many hours like Diablo was and it was crippled in many ways compared to  other games in the genre, such as Torchlight 1/2.
						</blockquote>
					</div>

					
				</div>
			</div>
			
			<div class="cleardiv"></div>
		</div>
	</div>
